Cognitive framing. The BRIEFING cell activates relevant prior knowledge before the first prediction. Students who know what they are looking for engage more deeply with the instruments. This is established pedagogy (advance organizers, Ausubel 1960).
Prediction calibration. The Core Question plants a seed of uncertainty. Students who read it think “I know the answer to this” – and then discover in Act I that they do not. The gap between the briefing’s question and the instrument’s answer is the learning moment.
Closure. The SYNTHESIS cell provides resolution. The Core Question from the BRIEFING now has an answer. The takeaways crystallize what was vague. The “What’s Next” transforms a finished lab into motivation for the next one.
Consistency. Every lab follows the same rhythm: brief, predict, discover, reflect, synthesize. Students who complete Lab 02 know exactly what to expect in Lab 05. This reduces cognitive overhead and lets students focus on content, not navigation.





